 by its definition it's beyond nature) or that are so unique that they can't be replicated by other scientists. Religion and other philosophies cannot be scientifically examined. So yes, in that sense, science is limited to the physical and natural. &#10;Which is exactly why the Bible can't be used as a basis for scientific inquiry in the broadest sense. It has been used as a source for archeology and historical explorations. But it's useless in a classroom where the hard sciences are being taught. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="807" language="en" documentId="1999" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Jack" date="8th September 2007 04:08 PM" docType="forumpost" origUrl="http://www.volconvo.com/forums/showthread.php?t=11753&amp;page=9" topic="prayer-in-schools" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="1999" notes="" title="The Bible in Public Schools"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="557"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="558" end="807"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43"/></xmi:XMI>